{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_copying",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Copying Lists",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "When you work with lists, you might think that assigning one list to another creates a copy. But in Python, it doesn't work that way!"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Understanding how to properly copy lists is important to avoid unexpected behavior in your programs."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "the_problem",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "The Problem",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "When you assign a list to another variable using `=`, both variables point to the **same list**. Changes to one affect the other."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "original = [1, 2, 3]\ncopy = original\n\ncopy.append(4)\nprint(f\"Original: {original}\")\nprint(f\"Copy: {copy}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Original: [1, 2, 3, 4]\nCopy: [1, 2, 3, 4]"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Both lists changed! This is because `copy` and `original` refer to the **same list** in memory."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "understanding_references",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Think of it like this: `original` is a label pointing to a list. When you do `copy = original`, you're creating another label pointing to the **same list**, not a new list."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "This is called **mutability** - lists can be changed, and all variables pointing to the same list see those changes."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_problem",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "What will this code print?"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "list1 = [10, 20]\nlist2 = list1\nlist2.append(30)\nprint(list1)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "mcq",
                    "content": "",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": "",
                        "options": [
                            "[10, 20, 30]",
                            "[10, 20]",
                            "Error"
                        ],
                        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
                        "correctFeedback": "Correct! Both list1 and list2 point to the same list, so changes to list2 affect list1.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "list1 and list2 point to the same list, so changes to one affect both.",
                        "explanation": "Since list2 = list1 creates a reference, not a copy, both variables see the change."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "copy_method",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "The Solution: copy()",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "To create a real copy, use the `copy()` method. This creates a **new list** with the same values."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "original = [1, 2, 3]\ncopy = original.copy()\n\ncopy.append(4)\nprint(f\"Original: {original}\")\nprint(f\"Copy: {copy}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Original: [1, 2, 3]\nCopy: [1, 2, 3, 4]"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Now `copy` is a separate list! Changes to `copy` don't affect `original`."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "copy_independence",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "With `copy()`, each list is independent. You can modify one without affecting the other."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "fruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\"]\nbackup = fruits.copy()\n\nfruits.append(\"orange\")\nprint(f\"Original: {fruits}\")\nprint(f\"Backup: {backup}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Original: ['apple', 'banana', 'orange']\nBackup: ['apple', 'banana']"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The backup list stays unchanged when we modify the original."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_copy",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "code_fill",
                    "content": "Create a true copy of the list so changes don't affect the original.",
                    "properties": {
